Problem: Find $2^x$ if

\begin{align*}
2^x+3^y&=5,\\
2^{x+2}+3^{y+1} &=18.
\end{align*}

Solution: We complete the square:  \begin{align*}
6j^2 - 4j + 12 &= 6\left(j^2 - \frac{2}{3} j\right) + 12 \\
&= 6\left(j^2 - \frac{2}{3} j + \frac{1}{9}\right) + 12 - \frac{6}{9} \\
&= 6\left(j - \frac{1}{3} \right)^2 + \frac{34}{3}
\end{align*}Then $q = \frac{34}{3}$ and $p = - \frac{1}{3}$. The question asks for $\frac{q}{p}$, which is equal to $\boxed{-34}$.

Problem: Compute the ordered pair of positive integers $(x,y)$ such that

\begin{align*}
x^y+1&=y^x,\\
2x^y&=y^x+7.
\end{align*}

Solution: We have  \begin{align*}
&(2x^2 + 7x - 3) - (x^2 + 5x - 12) \\
&\qquad = 2x^2 + 7x - 3 - x^2 - 5x + 12\\
&\qquad = (2x^2 - x^2) +(7x-5x) +(12-3)\\
&\qquad = \boxed{x^2+2x+9}.
\end{align*}

