Solution: To calculate how much taller the oak tree is than the elm tree, we must subtract the height of the elm tree from the height of the oak tree. We'll do this by using the fact that $11\frac{2}{3} = 11 + \frac{2}{3}$ and $17\frac{5}{6} = 17 + \frac{5}{6}$ and that $3$ and $6$ have a common denominator of $6$. We get \begin{align*}
17\frac{5}{6} - 11\frac{2}{3} &= 17 + \frac{5}{6} - (11 + \frac{2}{3}) \\ &= 17 + \frac{5}{6} - 11 - \frac{2}{3} \\ &= 17 - 11 + \frac{5}{6} - \frac{2}{3} \\ &= 6 + \frac{5}{6} - \frac{2}{3} \\ &= 6 + \frac{5}{6} - \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{2}{2} \\ &= 6 + \frac{5}{6} - \frac{4}{6} \\ &= 6 + \frac{1}{6} \\ &= \boxed{6\frac{1}{6}\text{ feet}}.
\end{align*}

